Maybe a fisheye lens for a birdhouse is too much.
You never learn.
I should have known better, since I built one before with a "normal" lens.
I will write more about it on the weekend once I've installed the second one.
Let's just say that the birds will have better internet connectivity than I did in 2015.
At least that's the plan.
The box that already has a nest in it sucks up a lot of WLAN data.
It will be a bit more difficult for the other one to go online.
Okay, I hung up the new birdhouse today. This is how it looks at its new spot in the garden.
But let's take a step back. Noone asks: "What exactly is inside?"
Above is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a fisheye lens camera and an IR LED that I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swiveling side wall of the birdhouse. I bought it that way and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no power in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
In the gray box hanging on the side of the birdhouse is the battery.
When it's charged, I have about 4 hours of runtime.
I call that a feature. This way, the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points that I replaced last autumn in the fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
This is almost a shame because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and direct it down into the garden.
Maybe I will do that if I set up more nest boxes with cameras in the future. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I probably need it.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It turned off just one hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery stopped charging three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or maybe less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I will have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I have no telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
Generally, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And perhaps a battery that at least theoretically is able to keep the device running overnight.
Oh yeah, and another lens.
Fisheye is quite overboard.
But I am already looking for parts on Digikey so I can build my own board specifically for this.
Or not. We will see.
And it is still offline.
Great.
According to the actual solar cells on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait another one or two hours to see what happens – or doesn't happen.
Still offline.
It's never easy anyway.
It turned out that on the USB-C Breakout I used to connect the charger, 5V and GND were swapped on the silk screen.
I swapped the cables and now the charge indicator is lighting up.
The ESP did not turn online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and it is still offline.
It seems like it is rebooting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think this panel just doesn't work. I've ordered a larger one now and hope that will fix it.
Take a look at what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already setting so low (and is partly blocked by a tree) that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I put the device into operation.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this setup or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021 and it should deliver 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or my multimeter, or the data has been changed.
Good news!
You have changed the data and the ones I have are wrong.
Both the old and the new listing titles call it a 12 V 10-W panel.
That's why I never delete old emails.
Look! It went offline about an hour ago and was back online for about half a minute.
Maybe the panel just managed to charge the battery for 38 seconds of runtime in more than two hours.
Guess what: It's cloudy today. I am not sure if the (probably faulty) solar panel will manage to generate enough power at all.
Let's wait and see.
Update: I have installed the new panel and now it seems to be working.
It might still go out once the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
Fun fact: I use the Ping integration in Home Assistant to check if it is online or not.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but also not terribly bad.
